docs.text: i have exaggerated , though : there is one interesting character , and one terrific performance .

docs.text: that character is steve rubell , played with more perceptiveness by mike myers than this limp production deserves .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: steve rubell is the owner of studio 54 , and if christopher had focused on him , then myers could have forced a good film out of this wreck all by himself .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: alas , we are instead guided to endure the trials of a young man named shane ( ryan phillippe ) , a going-nowhere new jersey teen who gets a job in the club , thanks to rubell's homosexual impulses .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: it's here that he meets his friends , the array of uninteresting characters : his co-worker , greg ( brecklin meyer ) , his wife , anita ( salma hayek ) , and , of course , the love interest , julie black ( neve campbell ) .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: shane is just an innocent young fool in the beginning , and he has a reasonably sturdy home life .

docs.text: ( some of the scenes with his father border on interesting , while heather matarazzo , who plays his sister , pushes phillippe off the screen . )

docs.text: but he decides to envelop himself in the disco scene , and succumb to peer pressure and to drugs .
